However, in older C standards, variable-length arrays are not allowed. But assuming the user is using C99 or later, it's okay. Alternatively, we can use dynamic memory with malloc. Let's go with variable-length arrays here for simplicity. So:

int n;
scanf("%d", &n);
int array[n+1]; // indexes 0..n, but use 1..n.

Then, loop from 1 to n, read each element:

for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    scanf("%d", &array[i]);
}

Then, variables to track counts and indices:

int odd = 0, even = 0;
int odd_ind = 0, even_ind = 0;

Loop through each element again, check if even or odd.

for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    if (array[i] % 2 == 0) {
        even++;
        even_ind = i;
    } else {
        odd++;
        odd_ind = i;
    }
}

Then, compare odd and even counts. If odd > even, print even_ind else odd_ind. So:

if (odd > even) {
    printf("%d\n", even_ind);
} else {
    printf("%d\n", odd_ind);
}

Putting it all together. Wait, but in C, the array indices start at 0. However, the original code uses 1-based index here. So the indices in the output will be 1-based. For example, if the first element is the outlier, the Java code would have even_ind = 1, and the C code would do the same. So in the C code, when we read the elements into array[1], array[2], etc., the indices are correct. So the output will be correct. But what if the user inputs n elements starting from index 1? Let me think.

